38
00:02:03,112 --> 00:02:08,904
This quote from the designer Greg Castikian in his really excellent book,

39
00:02:08,904 --> 00:02:12,893
Uncertainty in Games, which was published in 2013, which I would recommend.

40
00:02:13,693 --> 00:02:18,775
And he talks about uncertainty as being an essential part of games.

41
00:02:18,775 --> 00:02:23,216
As he says, in designing games, a degree of uncertainty is essential.

42
00:02:23,216 --> 00:02:26,958
And that if there is no uncertainty, then it is not a game.

43
00:02:26,958 --> 00:02:30,479
You can have other forms of entertainment that don't have any uncertainty, a book or

44
00:02:30,479 --> 00:02:34,080
a movie, if you're watching it for the second time, it's going to do exactly the same thing.

45
00:02:34,080 --> 00:02:38,542
But a game, if you know exactly what the outcome is going to be, then there is no reason to

46
00:02:38,542 --> 00:02:38,882
play.

47
00:02:39,942 --> 00:02:46,564
So he looks at it and breaks down four major areas of uncertainty in games and ways that

48
00:02:46,564 --> 00:02:48,624
you can introduce uncertainty.

49
00:02:48,624 --> 00:02:54,446
Hidden information, examples would be in poker, things like that, where you've got cards or

50
00:02:54,446 --> 00:02:56,726
something that your opponent doesn't know that you have.

51
00:02:56,726 --> 00:03:00,007
There is skill or performance-based uncertainty.

52
00:03:00,485 --> 00:03:05,689
that is like darts or basketball or anything where you have to flick a disc or something

53
00:03:05,689 --> 00:03:08,331
like that, there is opponent uncertainty.

54
00:03:08,331 --> 00:03:13,074
Even in perfect information games like chess, you don't know what plans your opponent has

55
00:03:13,074 --> 00:03:16,316
or what move your opponent is going to make, and you have to make plans on how you're going

56
00:03:16,316 --> 00:03:16,897
to react to that.

57
00:03:17,597 --> 00:03:20,779
And then the last one is the traditional randomizers, which

58
00:03:20,779 --> 00:03:24,401
are dice and spinners, card draws, tile flips,

59
00:03:24,401 --> 00:03:25,181
stuff like that.

60
00:03:25,181 --> 00:03:27,623
And it's that green box, the randomizers, that I want to

61
00:03:27,623 --> 00:03:28,503
focus on today.

62
00:03:28,503 --> 00:03:31,685
Each of these deserves their own lecture and presentation,

63
00:03:31,685 --> 00:03:34,547
but I really want to focus on the randomizers and the way

64
00:03:34,547 --> 00:03:36,148
that those can impact the game.

65
00:03:40,678 --> 00:03:43,419
So as I said, there's a couple of different types of this.

66
00:03:43,419 --> 00:03:44,739
Die roll card draws.

67
00:03:44,739 --> 00:03:46,900
You also have classic spinners.

68
00:03:46,900 --> 00:03:49,561
One of my goals in life is to design a spinner-based game.

69
00:03:49,561 --> 00:03:52,621
I'm actually working on a game where you build your own

70
00:03:52,621 --> 00:03:54,822
spinner, like a giant roulette wheel, with different

71
00:03:54,822 --> 00:03:56,162
probabilities for different things.

72
00:03:56,162 --> 00:03:59,963
And then the venerable cube tower, where you throw cubes

73
00:03:59,963 --> 00:04:01,824
and then they come out.

74
00:04:01,824 --> 00:04:03,184
These are all ways that you can create

75
00:04:03,184 --> 00:04:05,525
uncertainty in your game.

76
00:04:06,726 --> 00:04:09,589
But how does that get applied?

77
00:04:09,589 --> 00:04:13,173
So let's take a look at some basic, this is just sort of a

78
00:04:13,173 --> 00:04:16,877
really basic representation of the flow of a game.

79
00:04:16,877 --> 00:04:19,740
There is a state of the game, then the player makes a

80
00:04:19,740 --> 00:04:25,085
decision, and that ends up with a result.

81
00:04:25,085 --> 00:04:28,008
Now there's two main places that the randomness can fit

82
00:04:28,008 --> 00:04:29,310
into this picture.

83
00:04:30,580 --> 00:04:36,043
The first is what I refer to as input randomness,

84
00:04:36,043 --> 00:04:38,544
and that is where the game state is randomized.

85
00:04:38,544 --> 00:04:41,265
So first the game state is randomized,

86
00:04:41,265 --> 00:04:43,806
then the players make a decision based on that,

87
00:04:43,806 --> 00:04:47,508
and then the results of the decision are going to be fixed.

88
00:04:47,508 --> 00:04:48,688
When a player makes a decision,

89
00:04:48,688 --> 00:04:52,250
they know what the outcome of that decision is going to be.

90
00:04:52,250 --> 00:04:55,211
The uncertainty in this case is on the input side.

91
00:04:55,211 --> 00:04:55,812
What is the game state?

92
00:04:58,466 --> 00:05:02,450
Now on the flip side, you can also have output randomness.

93
00:05:02,450 --> 00:05:04,813
In output randomness, the game state is fixed,

94
00:05:04,813 --> 00:05:06,555
and you're just making a decision

95
00:05:06,555 --> 00:05:07,596
around the current game state.

96
00:05:07,596 --> 00:05:11,060
But the result of your decision is going to be random.

97
00:05:11,060 --> 00:05:13,663
You make the decision, and then you see what the outcome is.

98
00:05:13,663 --> 00:05:15,625
You don't know how those two things

99
00:05:15,625 --> 00:05:17,067
are going to be correlated.

100
00:05:20,538 --> 00:05:22,560
So some examples of output randomness.

101
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:25,282
This is typically the type of randomness

102
00:05:25,282 --> 00:05:28,184
that is used in games, and certainly

103
00:05:28,184 --> 00:05:29,725
was going back millennia.

104
00:05:29,725 --> 00:05:30,846
You have risk.

105
00:05:30,846 --> 00:05:34,028
Of course, in risk, when you decide

106
00:05:34,028 --> 00:05:35,289
you're going to attack a territory,

107
00:05:35,289 --> 00:05:37,891
then you roll the dice and decide,

108
00:05:37,891 --> 00:05:39,852
figure out what the results are going to be.

109
00:05:39,852 --> 00:05:43,254
Roulette, you place your bets and then see it.

110
00:05:43,254 --> 00:05:46,517
In Dungeons and Dragons, every action that you take,

111
00:05:46,517 --> 00:05:49,439
you roll a die to see what the effect of that is.

112
00:05:50,619 --> 00:05:53,001
It's not necessarily super random things.

113
00:05:53,001 --> 00:05:55,343
There's also more sophisticated games.

114
00:05:55,343 --> 00:05:58,925
War games, in particular, have a lot of output randomness.

115
00:05:58,925 --> 00:06:02,708
I've shown here a typical combat results table from a 70s, 80s war game,

116
00:06:02,708 --> 00:06:05,750
where you decide you're going to do an attack,

117
00:06:05,750 --> 00:06:08,231
and then you roll a die or dice and see what happens.

118
00:06:08,952 --> 00:06:10,953
So those are all some examples of output randomness.

119
00:06:10,953 --> 00:06:14,695
Input randomness tends to be a more modern phenomenon

120
00:06:14,695 --> 00:06:16,176
in terms of games, with some exceptions.

121
00:06:16,176 --> 00:06:21,019
But one looking at here is Dominion is a great example.

122
00:06:21,019 --> 00:06:23,760
In Dominion, in one mode of play,

123
00:06:23,760 --> 00:06:26,882
there is a randomization for the kingdom cards

124
00:06:26,882 --> 00:06:28,723
that you select at the beginning of the game.

125
00:06:28,723 --> 00:06:31,785
But once you select those decks, that

126
00:06:31,785 --> 00:06:34,687
creates that game state that players then react to.

127
00:06:36,998 --> 00:06:38,859
Dominion actually, interestingly, has a couple of

128
00:06:38,859 --> 00:06:41,061
different levels of input randomness versus output

129
00:06:41,061 --> 00:06:42,161
randomness.

130
00:06:42,161 --> 00:06:43,602
One is the overall game state.

131
00:06:43,602 --> 00:06:46,884
But also, each time you draw a hand of five cards, that's

132
00:06:46,884 --> 00:06:48,045
sort of input randomness.

133
00:06:48,045 --> 00:06:49,986
And then you have to decide how you're going to play out

134
00:06:49,986 --> 00:06:50,967
those cards.

135
00:06:50,967 --> 00:06:53,769
There may be some output randomness in that.

136
00:06:53,769 --> 00:06:55,170
Like if you're playing a blacksmith and you have to

137
00:06:55,170 --> 00:06:57,151
draw cards, you're not necessarily sure what you're

138
00:06:57,151 --> 00:06:57,952
going to draw.

139
00:06:57,952 --> 00:06:59,973
But in general, you have a pretty good indication of the

140
00:06:59,973 --> 00:07:02,535
way that your turn is going to flow based on the input

141
00:07:02,535 --> 00:07:04,456
randomness of the cards that you draw.

142
00:07:04,736 --> 00:07:07,399
Similarly, backgammon is input randomness.

143
00:07:07,399 --> 00:07:11,063
You kind of roll the dice and then decide what you're going to do based around that,

144
00:07:11,063 --> 00:07:13,805
make your plans based around that.

145
00:07:13,805 --> 00:07:19,191
Contract bridge, to a certain extent, has a level of this in that, you know, as a declarer

146
00:07:19,191 --> 00:07:24,296
you see all your cards and your dummies cards and you can kind of build a plan around that.

147
00:07:24,296 --> 00:07:25,077
There is some...

148
00:07:25,777 --> 00:07:28,459
unknown factors, of course, in what your opponents hold,

149
00:07:28,459 --> 00:07:30,681
but typically you can have a pretty good idea of a plan.

150
00:07:30,681 --> 00:07:33,143
And then finally, I just threw in a video game here,

151
00:07:33,143 --> 00:07:35,784
the recently released Into the Breach,

152
00:07:35,784 --> 00:07:39,187
which is a great example of input randomness

153
00:07:39,187 --> 00:07:43,150
in that it very, very deliberately shows you

154
00:07:43,150 --> 00:07:46,092
exactly what the opponents are going

155
00:07:46,092 --> 00:07:47,213
to be doing on their turn.

156
00:07:47,213 --> 00:07:50,435
So in this case, for those of you that haven't played

157
00:07:50,435 --> 00:07:52,076
Into the Breach, you can see that there's a,

158
00:07:52,977 --> 00:07:58,999
those red striped lines there, those are the areas that the enemy is going to be attacking

159
00:07:58,999 --> 00:08:01,119
on their turn unless something happens to them.

160
00:08:01,119 --> 00:08:05,341
If they get moved out of the way or they get destroyed, you know exactly what's going to

161
00:08:05,341 --> 00:08:11,023
happen and your moves are also very, have limited randomness.

162
00:08:11,023 --> 00:08:13,444
You just know if you move here and you shoot here, you're going to do this damage, you're

163
00:08:13,444 --> 00:08:16,605
going to push this guy into the water, he's going to die, you know exactly what's going

164
00:08:16,605 --> 00:08:17,025
to happen.

165
00:08:17,025 --> 00:08:19,646
So those are some examples of input randomness.

166
00:08:23,416 --> 00:08:28,521
Now, it's good to divide it up and to think about it

167
00:08:28,521 --> 00:08:32,365
as you're designing, as a way of approaching randomness

168
00:08:32,365 --> 00:08:35,268
and these decisions that you build into games.

169
00:08:35,268 --> 00:08:36,529
But they're not.

170
00:08:38,155 --> 00:08:40,637
you know, they're not very clearly, you know,

171
00:08:40,637 --> 00:08:42,858
absolutely perfectly delineated in games.

172
00:08:42,858 --> 00:08:45,139
Because, you know, you think about risk.

173
00:08:45,139 --> 00:08:48,581
There is a fixed setup to when you start your turn

174
00:08:48,581 --> 00:08:49,862
about what the board looks like.

175
00:08:49,862 --> 00:08:51,803
And then you have to decide what you're going to do,

176
00:08:51,803 --> 00:08:54,765
and then you roll the dice to the outcome.

177
00:08:54,765 --> 00:08:57,527
But the input from your turn is the output randomness

178
00:08:57,527 --> 00:08:58,587
from somebody else's turn.

179
00:08:58,587 --> 00:09:02,169
So there's this constant flow, this constant cycle.

180
00:09:02,169 --> 00:09:04,030
But it still can be, um...

181
00:09:05,271 --> 00:09:07,953
It's still, I think, very useful from a design standpoint.

182
00:09:07,953 --> 00:09:10,555
There also can be longer term consequences,

183
00:09:10,555 --> 00:09:14,097
like in Settlers of Catan, there is also

184
00:09:14,097 --> 00:09:15,618
sort of input randomness for your turn,

185
00:09:15,618 --> 00:09:17,439
where you roll and see what goods are available,

186
00:09:17,439 --> 00:09:19,541
and then you decide how you're going to deal with it.

187
00:09:19,541 --> 00:09:21,502
And when you're building a settlement,

188
00:09:21,502 --> 00:09:24,344
you know if I play these four cards,

189
00:09:24,344 --> 00:09:27,066
I'm going to be able to put a settlement in this area

190
00:09:27,066 --> 00:09:28,907
in Settlers of Catan.

191
00:09:28,907 --> 00:09:31,048
But I don't necessarily know how that's

192
00:09:31,048 --> 00:09:32,309
going to produce for me down the road.

193
00:09:32,309 --> 00:09:34,551
So that's kind of longer term output randomness.

194
00:09:34,991 --> 00:09:38,512
So there's a lot of gray areas in this, but in general, I

195
00:09:38,512 --> 00:09:40,453
think this is a useful classification.

196
00:09:40,453 --> 00:09:46,076
Typically, input randomness built into a game will lead to

197
00:09:46,076 --> 00:09:49,897
strategy, a more strategic feel to the game, gives the

198
00:09:49,897 --> 00:09:54,779
players more sense of control, and rewards more skillful

199
00:09:54,779 --> 00:09:58,001
play, whereas output randomness is typically going

200
00:09:58,001 --> 00:10:00,321
to feel more random.

201
00:10:00,321 --> 00:10:02,022
There's little things that you can do.

202
00:10:03,663 --> 00:10:10,073
It becomes more tactical in that you have a shorter planning horizon, and it's typically

203
00:10:10,073 --> 00:10:11,615
associated with lower skill caps.

204
00:10:11,615 --> 00:10:15,521
Now, these are broad generalizations.

205
00:10:15,521 --> 00:10:18,566
There's a lot of examples on both sides.

206
00:10:19,407 --> 00:10:24,752
For example, war games. War games are filled with output randomness.

207
00:10:24,752 --> 00:10:27,515
Every time you do an attack, you typically roll the dice and see what happens.

208
00:10:27,515 --> 00:10:33,180
And those still feel very, you know, obviously have a lot of strategy, have a lot of tactics.

209
00:10:33,180 --> 00:10:35,002
There's ways to rise above that.

210
00:10:36,123 --> 00:10:39,985
But if you take the example of like Into the Breach, the video game example,

211
00:10:39,985 --> 00:10:45,609
that game would have a very, very different feel if you didn't know the results of your combats going into them.

212
00:10:45,609 --> 00:10:49,552
If you just planned your moves and then there was some sort of randomization about what happened.

213
00:10:49,552 --> 00:10:53,995
It's a very, very different game and it's a very less puzzly sort of a game.

214
00:10:53,995 --> 00:10:58,598
It becomes more of a, you know, just more random.

215
00:11:00,992 --> 00:11:06,494
there's a blend there of what you want to approach.

216
00:11:06,494 --> 00:11:13,757
Interestingly, also, which is a little bit outside the scope of this, but the more

217
00:11:14,900 --> 00:11:16,882
uh... randomness that you have in your game

218
00:11:16,882 --> 00:11:20,685
you can actually make it feel less random the more dice rolls that you have

219
00:11:20,685 --> 00:11:21,846
you're going to start to

220
00:11:21,846 --> 00:11:25,009
approach an average value that's a whole separate talk but

221
00:11:25,009 --> 00:11:28,652
uh... just keep that in mind and war games take a lot of advantage of that

222
00:11:28,652 --> 00:11:31,515
there's so many dice rolls that you can pretty much predict over the long run

223
00:11:31,515 --> 00:11:32,856
what's going to be happening

224
00:11:35,656 --> 00:11:39,460
Now there's more than at least two axes of randomness.

225
00:11:39,460 --> 00:11:40,762
Input, output is one of them.

226
00:11:40,762 --> 00:11:42,204
I ran through that one kind of quickly,

227
00:11:42,204 --> 00:11:44,727
but I want to spend a little bit more time

228
00:11:44,727 --> 00:11:47,750
talking about the correlation axis of randomness,

229
00:11:47,750 --> 00:11:49,933
because this is not one that's considered all that often,

230
00:11:49,933 --> 00:11:52,115
and I find it really interesting

231
00:11:52,115 --> 00:11:54,598
to look at games in this light.

232
00:11:55,846 --> 00:12:00,608
So what is correlation in terms of this randomness

233
00:12:00,608 --> 00:12:01,889
and the way I'm approaching it?

234
00:12:01,889 --> 00:12:04,170
The idea is basically that there's gonna be

235
00:12:04,170 --> 00:12:06,411
a series of events or a series of random numbers

236
00:12:06,411 --> 00:12:07,971
that are happening over time.

237
00:12:07,971 --> 00:12:10,212
Time one, time two, time three, time four.

238
00:12:10,212 --> 00:12:13,674
And if you know what's happening at time x,

239
00:12:13,674 --> 00:12:16,035
how much does that tell you at time x plus one?

240
00:12:16,035 --> 00:12:18,116
If I know that this is happening this turn,

241
00:12:18,116 --> 00:12:19,476
how much does that tell me

242
00:12:19,476 --> 00:12:20,537
about what's happening next turn?

243
00:12:20,537 --> 00:12:22,998
And there's a lot of different answers to that question.

244
00:12:23,698 --> 00:12:26,918
Sometimes, the answer is, you know nothing.

245
00:12:26,918 --> 00:12:28,999
You know absolutely nothing about what's happening next.

246
00:12:28,999 --> 00:12:32,660
And that, in the scientific or mathematical terminology,

247
00:12:32,660 --> 00:12:34,980
is called white noise.

248
00:12:34,980 --> 00:12:37,281
And what that means is that, again, there's

249
00:12:37,281 --> 00:12:41,301
no correlation between the last result and this result.

250
00:12:41,301 --> 00:12:44,682
If I'm playing Risk and I roll the dice,

251
00:12:44,682 --> 00:12:47,002
the battle result that I got last time

252
00:12:47,002 --> 00:12:50,523
is not impacted at all, does not impact in any way

253
00:12:50,523 --> 00:12:51,723
the result that I got this time.

254
00:12:52,445 --> 00:12:55,646
They are completely unrelated to each other.

255
00:12:55,646 --> 00:12:57,127
Just as a fun fact, we'll come back to it.

256
00:12:57,127 --> 00:12:59,108
It's actually called white noise.

257
00:12:59,108 --> 00:13:01,849
It's related to a frequency spectrum.

258
00:13:01,849 --> 00:13:04,891
So when you have noise, it generates different

259
00:13:04,891 --> 00:13:06,872
frequencies in it.

260
00:13:06,872 --> 00:13:09,373
And white noise has all the different frequencies, from

261
00:13:09,373 --> 00:13:12,555
low frequencies to high frequencies, low correlations

262
00:13:12,555 --> 00:13:15,256
to high correlations, small jumps and big jumps.

263
00:13:15,256 --> 00:13:18,758
So in a light spectrum sense, that would be white.

264
00:13:18,758 --> 00:13:20,719
And so that is why it is called white noise.

265
00:13:21,159 --> 00:13:27,805
And this is, as you can imagine, the most common way of treating randomness in games.

266
00:13:27,805 --> 00:13:28,926
But it's not the only way.

267
00:13:28,926 --> 00:13:32,368
Next option is called brown noise.

268
00:13:32,368 --> 00:13:34,170
In brown noise, you know a lot.

269
00:13:34,170 --> 00:13:39,994
The results at time step one are very, very highly correlated to what's going to be happening

270
00:13:39,994 --> 00:13:40,535
at time step two.

271
00:13:42,789 --> 00:13:47,012
By the way, white noise is called white because of the color of light, but brown noise is

272
00:13:47,012 --> 00:13:49,394
not called brown because of the color of the spectrum.

273
00:13:49,394 --> 00:13:51,515
It's called brown off of Brownian motion.

274
00:13:51,515 --> 00:13:56,979
In a spectrum standpoint, it's called red noise, which you'll sometimes see as a term.

275
00:13:56,979 --> 00:13:59,921
But brown noise is a little bit more of a common term.

276
00:13:59,921 --> 00:14:05,886
A really simple way to generate brown noise is to say you're starting at a certain value.

277
00:14:05,886 --> 00:14:08,567
You're starting at a value of eight, and you flip a coin.

278
00:14:08,567 --> 00:14:12,190
And on a heads, it goes to nine, and on a tails, it goes to seven.

279
00:14:13,246 --> 00:14:16,867
So you have a really good idea of what the next result is going to be,

280
00:14:16,867 --> 00:14:20,129
but you can't over the long run predict exactly where it's going to be.

281
00:14:20,129 --> 00:14:23,970
This is also sometimes called a random walk type of randomness

282
00:14:23,970 --> 00:14:27,972
because it's tied to where you start from,

283
00:14:27,972 --> 00:14:31,253
and it will spread out from there, but it spreads out

284
00:14:31,253 --> 00:14:33,314
in a controlled and slower way.

285
00:14:36,698 --> 00:14:40,562
And then the last type of noise is in between these two,

286
00:14:40,562 --> 00:14:41,703
white noise and brown noise.

287
00:14:41,703 --> 00:14:43,205
It's called pink noise.

288
00:14:43,205 --> 00:14:47,489
And pink noise, which goes back to our spectrum again,

289
00:14:47,489 --> 00:14:48,270
you have a

290
00:14:49,979 --> 00:14:56,628
very high chance of a small change, but a much smaller chance of a big change. So over

291
00:14:56,628 --> 00:15:03,577
time, that's going to start to gradually drop down and you could get really, really big

292
00:15:03,577 --> 00:15:08,003
jumps, but most of the time it's going to be focused on those small areas.

293
00:15:09,614 --> 00:15:12,055
Now, pink noise actually is sort of interesting,

294
00:15:12,055 --> 00:15:17,296
because it ties a lot into what humans like,

295
00:15:17,296 --> 00:15:20,217
and the way that humans experience the world.

296
00:15:20,217 --> 00:15:23,258
Pink noise is actually the best representation of randomness,

297
00:15:23,258 --> 00:15:24,718
and the randomness that we see.

298
00:15:24,718 --> 00:15:27,279
There's been studies, Vossen Clark did studies in 1975,

299
00:15:27,279 --> 00:15:29,759
where they took music, and they plotted

300
00:15:29,759 --> 00:15:32,860
the frequency of the notes over time,

301
00:15:32,860 --> 00:15:35,341
and how the frequency changed from one note to the next.

302
00:15:35,841 --> 00:15:39,284
and it's exactly corresponding to pink noise.

303
00:15:39,284 --> 00:15:41,045
They did the same with human speech.

304
00:15:41,045 --> 00:15:43,507
Human speech in terms of its tone,

305
00:15:43,507 --> 00:15:46,390
in terms of its volume, in terms of the pacing of it,

306
00:15:46,390 --> 00:15:49,713
also is a pink noise type curve.

307
00:15:49,713 --> 00:15:51,194
Financial systems follow this.

308
00:15:51,194 --> 00:15:53,976
You get a lot of small changes in the stock market,

309
00:15:53,976 --> 00:15:55,678
and every once in a while you get big movements

310
00:15:55,678 --> 00:15:56,959
and crashes and big jumps.

311
00:16:00,070 --> 00:16:04,113
You also have what are so-called black swan events,

312
00:16:04,113 --> 00:16:06,414
like the giant stock market crash in 2008,

313
00:16:06,414 --> 00:16:09,696
which are supposed to be exceptional events.

314
00:16:09,696 --> 00:16:12,538
So systems tend to be, you have an idea

315
00:16:12,538 --> 00:16:14,479
of where the Dow Jones is gonna end up every day.

316
00:16:14,879 --> 00:16:17,161
But every once in a while you get these big giant jumps.

317
00:16:17,161 --> 00:16:21,004
So a pink noise, in a very real way,

318
00:16:21,004 --> 00:16:25,347
represents a closer representation to reality.

319
00:16:25,347 --> 00:16:29,710
And it's also been found that systems that model pink noise,

320
00:16:29,710 --> 00:16:32,552
musical systems particularly, and voices and speech

321
00:16:32,552 --> 00:16:34,614
and things like that, that people respond to them better.

322
00:16:34,614 --> 00:16:36,895
People like them.

323
00:16:36,895 --> 00:16:39,037
Even if you just, I was going to play some noise for you,

324
00:16:39,037 --> 00:16:39,557
but I'm not going to.

325
00:16:40,138 --> 00:16:41,439
I'm not going to burden you with that.

326
00:16:41,439 --> 00:16:45,222
But if you listen to samples of white noise, audio, white

327
00:16:45,222 --> 00:16:48,264
noise, and brown noise, and pink noise, people universally

328
00:16:48,264 --> 00:16:50,386
like the sound of the pink noise better, even though it

